    {
      "id": "hc-note-1",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 980,
        "y": 170
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "What does this do?",
        "text": "Hard clipping chops the signal peaks flat, creating aggressive, buzzy distortion. The op-amp amplifies the signal, then shunt diodes brutally clamp it at ±0.7V.",
        "color": "yellow",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "hc-note-2",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 1080,
        "y": 270
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Shunt diodes",
        "text": "D1 and D2 connect from the signal path directly to ground. When the amplified signal exceeds ~0.7V, the diodes conduct and dump the excess to ground — creating a hard, flat-topped cutoff.",
        "color": "purple",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "hc-note-3",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 880,
        "y": 270
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Same diodes, different result",
        "text": "Compare this to the Soft Clipping example — both use 1N914 silicon diodes! But here they shunt to ground (hard), not in the feedback loop (soft). Topology matters more than the diode type.",
        "color": "purple",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "6d6bcd76-8972-4d42-b80f-a1ac76e3aa94",
      "type": "box",
      "position": {
        "x": 530,
        "y": -20
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Feedback Network",
        "color": "blue",
        "variant": "filled"
      },
      "style": {
        "width": 310,
        "height": 680
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "hc-note-gain",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 610,
        "y": 510
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Gain control (R2)",
        "text": "R2 sets the gain: R2/R1 = 100k/10k = 10×. Increasing R2 pushes the signal harder into the clipping diodes. In the RAT, this is a pot — that's the Distortion knob.",
        "color": "blue",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "hc-note-bias",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 660,
        "y": 110
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Bias divider (R4 + R5)",
        "text": "Equal resistors split VCC in half (4.5V), centering the signal in the op-amp's linear range. Unequal values would shift the bias point — clipping one half of the waveform harder than the other.",
        "color": "blue",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "hc-note-bypass",
      "type": "stickynote",
      "position": {
        "x": 340,
        "y": 230
      },
      "data": {
        "label": "Bypass cap (C3)",
        "text": "Holds the bias voltage steady at audio frequencies. Without it, signal leaks into the bias node and causes oscillation. Larger values keep the bias stable at lower frequencies.",
        "color": "blue",
        "size": "sm",
        "width": "normal"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "95f4df3f-8556-4d7f-b3f3-9e1376db5815",
